segments.text: Marmaduke Knox Thornton, born in Helen, Arkansas, February the 8th, 1892.
And could you give us a brief biographical statement of your early experiences in education, your boyhood?
We moved to Marlin, Texas in 1893, and for the next seven years I was
As soon as I was able to understand, my mother taught me the same courses that the children were having.
And when seven years old, I was ready for fifth grade.
But we had moved to Mississippi at that time, and they wouldn't acknowledge that and put me in the fourth.
Now, that's pretty well that part of it.
Is there anything you want to amplify on that?
Oh, if you could describe the school in Mississippi that you were put into, was it a one-room school, a larger?
No, it was, they were beginning at that time to more or less consolidate the various activities, and I went to what we call the greenhouse, which had
Grades from, as I recall, from the third up to the eighth.
We had no grades above the eighth at that time.
What town was this in?
Starkville, Mississippi.
Starkville?
Yeah.
I guess pretty much that takes care of that.
I entered fourth grade in 1890.
Nine, seven years old.
And you went all the way through the eighth grade there?
I went through the eighth grade and headed into the ninth grade, which they established the year when I finished.
The eighth grade, they established the ninth grade.
But I had an accident and had to drop out of school.
So... What did you do after that?
I wrote to schools where I'd give them assistantship or something, help pay my way.
at the same time studying for a doctor.
The only folks that answered my letter was this one.
And I took this job, but they didn't have any pre-med courses at that time.
When did you, and what year did you come to Texas?
I got off the train at College Station, Texas at 12.15.
February the 15th, 1911, and went on the payroll February the 16th, 1911.
And you were doing what?
Instructor in chemistry and chemical engineering.
My goodness, from education to chemical engineering, that's quite a switch, isn't it?
Well, you see, I worked as a chemist for the blast furnaces.
during the two years that I was out, so I didn't come in from law.
You had good practical experience then.
Yes, and another thing, there are courses that today they take in high school that were just on the horizon when I came here.
What we call the electrolytic dissociation theory, and it is every boy in a
10th grade in high school, knows what that's all about, was only about five or six years old in Germany, and we were just now beginning to pick it up.
So that and many other things, chemistry since 1910 has been revolutionized, and it's revolutionized about every 10 years.
There is no science
that I can dream of that has had as much improvement and change and development as the chemistry.
It's astounding.
Yes, Dr. Lindsay said basically the same thing when I talked to you.
What were your first impressions when you came to school here?
What was the campus like?
What were the students like?
Oh, Lord.
You want the raw details?
Sure, just want you to remember.
Excuse me just a second.
I got off the train at 12.15 on the 15th of February, 1911.
I asked the station man where I could get something to eat.
He says, you can't get anything to eat here, but you can go over to Boyd's store, which is right across the railroad track at that time, and he gets you some crackers and cheese.
I said, well, that ain't going to get by.
I said, do you mind if I leave my suitcase and trunk here till I go up?
I said, if what you say is true, I'm going to be on that 3 o'clock train headed east.
I said, where is the college?
He said, right up the way there, you just follow that road there.
I said, what's that fence for?
He said, to keep the boys in.
I said, hold everything.
Am I at a college or at a penitentiary?
He said, this is a college.
I said, what's the idea of keeping the boys in?
Well, they don't want them running around.
I said, uh-huh.
I still want you to keep these until I catch this train.
So I started out.
The thing that struck me as I came in, not only was there a fence, but there was a cedar grove on each side of the road.
It's a beauty.
It really was a beautiful grove on both sides.
And I got in the middle of that road there, I could see the old main building.
And that was all.
And the flagpole.
And that was all.
But as I went into the campus, I saw two things.
A big drill field and, gosh, all this bunch of tents in the world.
And I couldn't figure out what sort of a place this was.
It housed the students in tents.
I had just come from school.
school that housed all the boys in dormitories.
But I followed the instructions and turned to the left.
Nice little house over there, across from where all these tents were.
I later learned that's where a fellow by the name of Kyle lived.
Then there was another little house, a nice little cottage, and I learned later that's where Dr. Fountain lived.
head of English department.
The next house I saw was Dr. Ellinger's house, I learned later.
Then there was a big building there, sitting back from the street.
And boys were coming out of that building, picking their teeth.
Well, I wasn't putting that going into the dormitory, into that mess hall and get something to eat.
I was going to get something to eat.
the instructor's aide.
The next house I ran into was a nice little house, very imposing.
I learned later it was the president's home.
And Andy Godwin across from the president's home, there was some construction work going up.
It later wound up to be Milner Hall.
And another one there, there was some construction work going on later that became Leggett Hall.
Well, I turned to the left there in following directions and ran into Emil Lehmann, a schoolmate in Mississippi.
And he informed me, he's glad to see me, and informed me that they was looking for me.
Well, the thing that struck me was if they was looking for me, they were a long way from the depot where I got off.
I told him what I wanted.
He sort of got a little serious.
He said, I don't know whether Miss Still will feed you or not.
I said, it don't make any difference, Emil.
She either feeds me, or I'm on that train going back to Birmingham this afternoon.
Well, he went back with me.
And
opened the double door in the old Shirley, and Mrs.
Still come barging out of the kitchen, sweating and steaming, on the right he had to open the door, and I told her I wanted something to eat.
Well, the dinner was over, and she didn't feed tranchants anyhow.
I said, I'm not supposed to be a tranchant here.
Well, I said, maybe.
I said, I want something to eat.
Well, Emil talked her into feeding me.
And after dinner, he took me and lead and showed me where the chemistry department was and left me.
He was in a new building called, now known as the Nagel Hall, or the Civil Engineering Building.
I went on in.
There was a great big man sitting at a desk on the second floor.
At that time, nobody on the first floor.
The whistle hadn't blown.
I walked in, introduced myself, and he's in a big roaring voice, a very melodious voice.
I learned to love it.
But it could very easily scare the fool out of us.
a recalcitrant student, and he said, I'm J.C. Blake.
I'm glad you're here.
Well, I said to him, Doc, I just want to know if it's all right with you if I just cancel out my agreement with you and I catch that train and leave here.
I said, I don't like anything I've seen about this place up to the present time.
Blake took off, fed me a bunch of hogwash.
And I learned when another man showed up here who went through the same experience, he gave him the same bunch of hogwash.
But he convinced me that if I didn't stay, the school would fold up.
And it was up to me to stay there and make the school a success.
And so I agreed with him that I'd stay till the 1st of June.
He said, good.
I noticed that Mr. Nelson has just come in.
Mr. Nelson will show you your duties.
Nelson was glad to see me.
He was the bottom man on the totem pole, and when I came in, I became the bottom man on the totem pole.
Now, what Nelson is this?
W.P.
Nelson.
Nelson was an instructor in the chemistry department at that time.
He left here during the war, the First World War.
Well, Nelson took me in tow.
He says, you're going to be responsible for the stock room.

that wasn't part of my agreement but it's okay he said in addition to that you'll have charge of the laboratories for freshmen for first year students and they'll be in these three dormitories and you'll assist dr frapps a man who taught organic chemistry in his laboratory right there and
You'll assist me.
I'll be downstairs.
I said, no, I won't either.
Well, I got to have some help.
I said, you don't need me.
Well, I got the keys to the stock room.
He said, now we'll go to the basement, and I'll show you what you do down there.
And he showed me a machine, a gas machine that made
artificial gas for burners out of gasoline.
Well, I was familiar with that.
We had one in Bessemer before we left, and I learned something about it.
But I looked at that machine, and I said, Nelson, how many burners you going to drag on that?
He said 75.
I said, what's the size of that machine?
He said 25.
And he said, it gives us lots of trouble.
I said, I can imagine.
I said, okay.
What else I want to do?
He showed me a bunch of bottles.
And he said, these lost their labels, and you can test them, and if we find out what they are, we'll put a label on them and put them back in stock, and you can test them.
Well, I saw a bottle about, a gallon bottle, I was going to say yea high, that's what it was, but a gallon bottle, and I looked at it,
I said, what's in that?
He said, here's some stuff that the veterinary department left up there and I don't know.
I said, well, let's find out.
I took the top off and opened it up and it was a concentrated extract of pool cat ammunition.
Well, I was glad to get that because I said, I'm going to find out what makes that stuff function.
Well, I didn't.
Later on, some student found it.
He put it to some very uncomfortable usage.
But I was going to analyze it.
I was perfectly sure I could.
Today, I'm not so sure.
But I went back upstairs then.
I said, OK.
I said, you go on upstairs.
I'll take over.
The first thing I did is I desensitized that gas machine.
Any fire inspector that had come by would have locked the thing up and stuck me in the clink.
But we got gas that afternoon for 75 burners.
As soon as the boys at 4 o'clock left, I went back and put the machine working like it ought to.
And I don't think anyone ever found out just what I was doing to that bloody machine to make it work.
But it worked there.
But that was my...
Then I went up and I found out that the boys wanted evaporating dishes.
They signed for an evaporating dish on a little blue slip or beaker or anything else.
After a while, Dr. Blake came in, asked me how I was getting along.
I said, I don't know.
I said, you don't have much stock.
He said, no, we don't have much stock.
He said, we got $1,500 to run this department on.
And it takes every cent of it, and we can't buy much goods.
He said, it just takes every cent we can dig up to operate the department.
Now, that, of course, does not include salaries.
That was operating cost.
But these boys were saying, I said, do these boys pay for that material, the stuff that they break?
No, he said, we never billed them.
I said, well, is it all right if I bill them?
He said, well, they've never done it.
But we'll try it.
So the first of the month, after checking in and checking out and working back, I sent a bill through for them.
But that comes later.
That wasn't the first day.

Now, if I had taken one of these striped kitties and tossed it on the dance floor, I couldn't have caused any more consternation than the idea of the chemistry department charging these birds for stuff they broke.
Well, 5 o'clock, I decided I'd go down and get my stuff and send it up to the Shirley Annex.
Now, that was a building just adjoining the Shirley where we ate.
The Shirley proper had some rooms upstairs.
The Shirley Annex had a bunch of new rooms.
I was trying to figure it.
Let's see, I can figure it pretty easily.
It's 4 times 2 is 8 times 3 is 32 rooms.
that single instructors and teachers were profs.
And across the road from it was a yellow house that the elite among the instructors and so on lived in.
If you didn't hold your girl just in a certain way when you danced with her, you couldn't get in that other building.
except for the fact that Charles Perea, the dean of the college, lived over there and had two rooms.
And, of course, he was one of the elite.
Is this kind of a social clique over there, rather than elite?
Well, we didn't have any cliques in those days.
Of course, it don't make any difference where you go.
In a few days, their group began to segregate.
It's not a clique in one sense of the word, in another sense of the word, it would be.
These were, though, over in the yellow house, were those that held their heads just a little higher than the rest of us.
Do you remember what kind of rent you had to pay in the Shirley Handels?
No, I don't.
I think it's probably, probably,
$15 to $20 a month.
Did that include meals?
Yes, it did include meals.
It may have been a little more than that.
It wasn't a whole lot.
By our standards today, it was not, but according to our standards back there, it was pretty good because there's a little difference in pay scales then and here.
If I'm not prying too much, can I ask you how much you came to A&M for?
I came to A&M for the munificent sum of $600 a year.
My goodness.
But the president of the institution only drew $3,600.
Dean Pereira drew $3,000.
So $600 a year was quite a livable sum then.
You could live on it, sure.
We didn't own automobiles in those days.
Did you take a cut in pay from?
Yeah, I took a cut in pay, but not much.
Five dollars a month.
Five dollars a month.
a week maybe or maybe more.
I just got tired of looking at the moon.
See I was working on the night shift and the night shift consisted in those days of going to work at six o'clock and working until seven the next morning.
It was a long time.
But I went down and took off in the whistle blue.
I went down to the depot to get my suitcase and arrange my trunk.
Emil Neyman and another fellow in the physics department by the name of Leon Scala

I said, Leon, that's one of the Skeeler boys, but Frank Skeeler was an instructor in physics, and he and Emil had gone down to the depot and got my trunk and suitcase and had it hauled and put in their room because there were no empty rooms, and there were three of us lived in that room the rest of the year.
Emil, I mean, Frank and Emil slept in the double bed, and I had a single bed.
Very cozy arrangement.
It's kind of crowded.
Yes, but we weren't accustomed to much.
At supper I met all the rest of the fellas.
Some of them I consider top hands in anybody's works.
I learned to love them.
The others I learned to tolerate.
Now that's my first day.
That was quite a full day, wasn't it?
Oh, my.
Well, can you tell us a little bit about your career at A&M, going from the first day and what courses you might have taught?
Well, the first year I was here, I ran the first year laboratory and assisted Dr. Blake in setting up lecture
and listened to his lectures so that I would be able to help him when he wanted a demonstration.
And I want to say that Dr. Blake was 25 years ahead of his time.
He was one of the best educated men in chemistry in this country at that time.
and his assistant was equally good, a fellow by the name of McDougal, F.H.
McDougal.
He taught the chemical engineers.
Blake was overseer and taught mostly the first year men.
Dr. Frapps taught agricultural chemistry.
Blake taught organic chemistry and general chemistry.
Nelson was analytical chemistry for the chemical engineers.
I could have said I got a raise to $720 for the next year.
That thing went on up.
for the year 1915-16, I had 1440, and they had jumped, that jumped me $200, and those got a jump of $400.
Well, at that time, as I said, I was no longer the bottom man on the totem pole, but I still was carrying an awful lot of Nelson's work as well as some of the other.
And when I learned that Nelson got a $400 raise and I only got a $200 raise, I blew my stack.
And at that time, Dr. Hedges was in charge of the department.
I told him that I was going to get $1,580 or $1,640, and he could make up his mind which it would be.
He went over to see Brassell, the president, and he came back and said, Dr. Brassell just says there isn't that much money.
He can't let you have it.
I said, I figured he'd do that.
Here's my letter of resignation.
He said, you can't quit.
I said, I have.
I said, I'll leave here the first day of November.
And about 30 minutes later, Dr. Brazell called up and told me to come over.
He wanted to see me.
He told me that he had just found some monies he didn't know he had.
And that I was going to get $1,620, I guess it was.
Delce was getting $1,660.
Does that work out right?
Whether it works out right or not, something like that.
He just put me in as his segundo.
I see.
Okay.
And did you have any second thoughts about coming back to this place?

No, because at the close of the war, I had made up my mind that I wasn't going to stay in the country where the snow that fell on the first day of December was still on the ground for the 15th day of April.
Where is the Picatinny Arsenal?
Northern part of Dover, New Jersey.
Cold country.
A thousand feet above New York City.
And we'd be having snow and ice and New York would be fairly warm.
So then you came back here at the close of the war then?
Mm-hmm.
I see.
and is what, number two man in chemistry school?
Professor of industrial chemistry in charge of the work in chemical engineering.
I see.
I held that job until 1935 when the depression soured me on the whole thing and I went into the extension service
and worked within agriculture from then until 1957.
What soured you?
On Kemet, you said you got soured on the whole thing.
Were you talking about the school?
No, no.
I got soured here.
We spent four years trying to develop young men that take that place and
the industry and society.
And when they graduated, there was no place for them.
I had boys by Jimenez in 32 and 33 go to work for $25 a month.
And one boy went to, came to me and said, how much I was out of yet?
I said, a hundred and a quarter.
But he said, so-and-so offered me 50.
I said, did you take it?
He said, yes.
I said, good.
Some of the boys went near me.
That's where Al Ludeke and Cepha,
No, there were three or four of them.
I alluded to this one.
They all came out as Major Generals.
I came to think, I was trying to say CIFR, but it wasn't CIFR.
It was something like that.
CIFR in that period.
They went down and every one of them came out as Major Generals.
Top of their hands.
No place for them.
Well, could you tell us a little bit about the depression here at the school?
How did it affect the school or the students, other than not being jobless when they got out?
No, man.
They just more or less, I would say that everybody more or less accepted it.
in a fatalistic sort of a way.
Was the school adversely affected?
Was it badly affected?
No, because we scratched and made do and kept on going.
Then it wasn't probably maybe as bad here as it was in other parts of the country then?
Probably not.
In other words, we didn't have the money.
The legislature cut our monies out.
Didn't cut them out, but reduced them.
And all we did was just pull up our belts and drive by.
Did the school ever have any trouble paying you?
What?
Did the school ever have any trouble making its payments to the faculty?
They always got you checks.
Yes, but that wasn't the school.
That was the state.
The banks in Brown tried to carry those certificates without discounting them, but they couldn't make it eternally, and finally they had to start discounting them.
Yes, they had that.
In a way, they paid you in a kind of a script then.
Yes, a script.
And if the bank discounted them, then you all lost money on what you were being, the little bit you were being paid anyway.
So the state was actually not paying in cash then?
Oh, no.
The outcome of it is we got a law passed.
If you have read the papers about the way the legislature functions, we can't do that.
We won't have the cash.
We're on a cash-as-we-go basis in the state.
And if the cash isn't going to be there, that appropriation will not be made.
And that's the root out of that condition.
Texas A&M wasn't the only one that was affected.
Every institution, every college, every state institution had the same thing.
I see.
It wasn't picked on A&M.
Did the state ever pay off on that script?
Oh, yes.
They picked it all up.
How long did they pay you in that?
Do you remember?
No, I don't.
What was it, a year or six months?
I really don't know.
I'd say at least a year, but I really don't know.
I can't.
Do you remember, you don't have any idea what year this was they were doing this?
No, about 32, 33, somewhere in there.
I see.
Did, was there more, were there fewer or less students coming to school?
There were fewer.
They didn't have money enough.
Of course, what boys came,
A lot of them had to work.
I could get a boy to push a lawnmower over my lawn for two bucks.
In other words, the labor pay scales were almost non-existent.
Is there anything before we go on past the end to the, you said you went to work for the Extension or Experiment Station?
Extension.
The Extension Service.
Is there anything about that

previous to that time you'd like to comment on, any experiences, any people you'd like to talk about that are possibly any of the presidents that I have listed here that maybe you had experiences with?
Well, as I said, it's rather interesting.
When I came here, Harrington had been president.
They had a strike, and after some of those students' strike, he was benched.
He was a director of the experiment station and raised to the president.
Well, let's see what that is.
Here in 1905.
And when I came, he had been set down
as a result of that strike and given his job as the director of the Experiment Station again.
And of course, I knew him.
Believe it or not, he was reared in Starkville, Mississippi.
And I knew him and his folks when I came here.
So he was rather
courtly sort of a fellow and very definite in his opinions.
It's one of the things that caused him his trouble.
A man in that position as president can't be too definite in his opinions.
But if he is, he don't want people to think it.
But so I accept the fact that he was a very affable man.
I liked him.
That's about as far as I could go.
But Milner came here.
He came here before I did.
He came in 1908.
I came in 1911, February of 11.

One of the first men I met on the campus after I got through the official thing with Blake and his crew and the bunch down at the Shirley was I ran into him on the campus, and he stopped and talked to me.
Of course, in that day and time,
You knew everyone on the campus.
And he stopped and talked to me, and I was pretty well impressed with it.
And the more longer I knew him, the more impressed I was with him.
Now, he was not a scholar, but he brought in
to the policy of the institution a statement that still rides with you, and that is that no boy who earnestly wants an education will be turned away.
And it's still that way.
The administrative bunch
would go out of their way to help a boy today that is earnestly wanting an education.
And it didn't help.
A boy failed a course, well, he's not doing any good.
Kick him out of college.
Oh, no, not with Milner.
Let him take it over next year.
But you know, Milner would not tolerate
a moving school of students from the institution for scholastic inefficiencies.
He just wouldn't stand it.
And they had a strike down here in 1912, I guess it was, and it broke his heart.
and he retired saying that if he had no more influence over the boys then that he wouldn't stay here and he left with that with a you might say a broken heart.
Do you have any idea what the strike was about?
Hazing.
Hazing and he tried to stop it.
He not only tried to stop it but he tried to to
work around it so that there'd be no trouble.
He tried to compromise all the way through so that everybody would be happy, but it wasn't to be.
How about after that?
Do you remember?
Charles Periot went in as acting president, and he's a rather interesting little fellow.
He was originally a professor of mathematics, and I think he still taught at this time.
He actually ran the institution's scholastic work.
And if you had any objection, there's one thing that stands.
Put it in writing.
Any proposition you had that involved the institution that you dealt with Perea, you submitted it in writing.
You wouldn't consider it otherwise.
But somewhere down in the mix up here, while he was... Milner was here, the Nassau band.
1912, I believe.
And there was a building, the Presence Visa Hall.
And they had some tin shacks over there that they were eating in.
And the students, every Friday, every Saturday night,
but have a bass in the mess hall.
And it is quite a bass.
You would have enjoyed it yourself.
And I was sitting next to Pereira one night, and he had an election for the presidency of the college.
Cesar Horn was acting chairman, I believe.
I'm not too sure whether he or Ray Dixon was acting chairman.
And Red Wayne Palmer, he's a student now.
Faribault Kincheloe.
And a couple more.
was nominated for president of the institution.
I was trying to think of one of them that was a half-wit.
I wouldn't mention his name, so I better let it ride, because of the fact that his people were pretty famous in the state.
And the speeches that bunch made, Perea said, oh, he didn't like to rupture himself laughing.
But...
That's about all the entertainment we had was some fool thing like that.
